Sonoran Hot Dogs are a Tucson, Arizona tradition. The recipe in my Taste of Tucson #cookbook comes from Daniel Contreras whose restaurant, El Guero Canelo was presented with a James Beard America’s Classics Award. Contreras calls his bacon-wrapped hot dogs in bolillo rolls with a smear of pinto beans and topped with onions tomatoes and chiles “weenies.” #tasteoftucson #tucsonsonora #jackiealpersphotography

We're all obsessed with the ingredient that Alpers told us is a favorite filling for Sonoran-style burritos: carne seca. This sun-dried shredded beef is a local delicacy in Tucson. "The beef is literally dried in the sun until it becomes jerky, then it's shredded and pan-fried with green chiles, onions, and tomatoes," before being folded into a burrito, explains Alpers.

Read more of my thoughts on making burritos at @tastingtable: https://www.tastingtable.com/1247100/tips-you-need-when-making-burritos/

Bring the heat to your usual bourbon neat with a dramatic, hot and spicy whisky cocktail inspired by the hit series, #Yellowstone. The full recipe below is an outtake, cut for space from my upcoming Unofficial Yellowstone Cookbook, @yellowstonecookbook which be published October 24th, 2023 (Media Lab Books). Now available for Preorder - link to Amazon in bio. 

Crush the Thai red chili into the glass before drinking… if you dare.

Ingredients
1 lime
Tajin Habanero
Hot pepper flakes
2 oz bourbon whisky such as Buffalo Trace
1 oz simple syrup
1 small dried hot red pepper such as a Thai chile, for garnish
Dehydrated or fresh lime slice for garnish

Instructions
Slice half the lime into 3 rounds. Make a slit in one of the slices of lime and slide it around the rim of a rocks glass to moisten. 

Put an equal amount of Tajin and hot pepper flakes on a plate, then roll the wet rim of the rocks glass in the chile pepper mixture so that it sticks to the rim. Set the lime slice aside for garnish.

Put two more slices of lime with as much tajin and hot pepper flakes as you can handle in the bottom of the rocks glass and muddle to release the flavors.

Fill a cocktail shaker with ice. Add the whisky, simple syrup and the juice from the remaining lime. 

Shake vigorously until the outside of the shaker becomes frosty then pour the contents into a rocks glass. 

Garnish with the saved lime round and the dried chile pepper and serve immediately.

See the #recipe on my website: https://recipes.jackiealpers.com/yellowstone-the-fire-the-fury-whisky-cocktail/

The secret to perfectly grilled corn in the husk for campfires or cookouts is soaking the ears first.

Ingredients
Ears corn in their husks

Instructions
Soak the corn in water for at least an hour. Drain, then cut the silk from the end of the ears with a kitchen scissors.

Grill over direct medium heat, with the lid closed for 25 to 35 minutes, turning occasionally. The husks will blacken.

Let cool slightly then peel back the husk and remove the silk before eating.

The Unofficial Yellowstone Cookbook is out in less than two weeks and I'm sharing an unpublished recipe for Irish soda bread with blueberries and currants. The Dutton Dutton family immigrated from Ireland to Montana where quick breads were popular during the early 20th century. Blueberries and currants incorporate a local flavor and tint the bread with a beautiful blue color.

Today is the 10 year anniversary of the publication of Sprinkles! Recipes and Ideas for Rainbowlicious Desserts. It was the first cookbook that I both wrote and photographed and it changed the course of my career. I am eternally grateful to Quirk Books, and to my editor Margaret Novak setting it all in motion. 

Sprinkles! was the first cookbook to explore the science, methodology and history of sprinkles (Sprinkology!) and after 10 years, it's still in print (you can find it on Amazon).

Thanks to everyone who made Sprinkles a part of your lives and who help make the world a more sparkly, colorful and joyful place. 

#sprinkles #cookbook #rainbowsprinkles #eatarainbow #rainbowlicious #rainbowcake

This is a tribute #recipe to the scene in #Yellowstone season 3 where the villain Roarke is drinking a green smoothie after naked yoga. This is the same drinkware used on the show! 

The recipe was developed from carefully analyzing all of the ingredients shown on Roarke's kitchen counter and my conclusion is that he (or the Yellowstone prop person) can make a pretty decent green smoothie. Note: the photo is a recreation of the scene – at this point in the show he had put on a bathrobe. We didn't get to see him naked. 

Post Naked Yoga Green Smoothie Recipe
Ingredients
2 well-packed cups chopped kale
1 banana
1 cup frozen mango chunks

What makes a cookbook catch your eye? For yours truly, it’s a combo of style, substance, and originality. So when I stumbled upon a lively new one from accomplished author and photographer @jackiealpers I tracked her down to learn all about "The Unofficial Yellowstone Cookbook: Recipes Inspired by the Dutton Family Ranch." Here are some highlights of our virtual chats across the miles.
.
What made you want to write this cookbook? 

I am an expert in Western Americana and Southwestern cuisine. I wanted to create recipes that focus on and honor the regional food of Montana and Texas as well as the "Yellowstone" TV series. 
.
How long did it take?

Nine months, the same amount of time it takes to have a baby. This is my Yellowstone love child! 
. 
What was the hardest part? 

Watching every single episode from "Yellowstone" and both prequels, 1883 and 1923, and documenting all the food that I saw on the shows. Then I meticulously researched each dish for both regional and historical accuracy before writing the recipe and photographing it. 
. 
What was the best part? 

Creating easy and fun recipes that "Yellowstone" fans will recognize and enjoy. I hope fans will get all of the little in-jokes and fun facts I included. 
. 
What advice do you have to people who want to attempt writing their own cookbook? 

Focus on what makes you and your recipes special, why you want to share your recipes, and how will they benefit the world. 
.
